    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-03T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-03T13:00:00-05:00" n="623"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d623">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3231/578a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-03T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 3, 1934—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2. Department’s 103, December 6, noon.<note n="2" xml:id="d623fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1933v05#pg_29">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 29</ref>.</note> What progress is being
                    made? The Colombian treaty was signed December 15.<note n="3" xml:id="d623fn3"
                        >For text, see <ref target="frus1933v05#pg_249">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 249</ref>.</note> We are most anxious
                    to make progress with the Brazilian treaty.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
